{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GUR1dsNVzUTLzShG1rFUcD","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/3-2-audit-fix-story-generation.md`.\n\n**Summary:** Created story 3-2-audit-fix-story-generation with 10 acceptance criteria, 7 task groups, and detailed dev notes. All ACs tagged `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` -- every criterion can be verified by running CLI commands (build, test, run `codeharness audit --fix`, inspect output/files/state).\n\nThe story covers:\n- Fix story generation from audit gaps (FR15)\n- Sprint state integration via atomic writes\n- BMAD format compliance (NFR6)\n- Idempotency (skip existing stories)\n- JSON output support\n- Edge cases (0 gaps, missing state file, uninitialized harness)\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:**\n- None.\n\n**Workarounds applied:**\n- The epic definition (Story 3.2) has only 3 ACs. I expanded to 10 to cover edge cases, JSON output, idempotency, atomic writes, and precondition checks that are clearly needed based on existing codebase patterns. The original 3 ACs were too sparse for implementation.\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- **Story key collision:** The `audit-fix-{dimension}-{index}` key scheme uses a sequential index. If gaps change between runs (new gaps appear, old ones resolve), the same index could map to different gaps. A content-based hash would be more robust but harder to read. The dev should decide during implementation.\n- **Sprint-state.json vs sprint-status.yaml divergence:** The epic says \"added to sprint-state.json as backlog stories\" (AC #2), but the sprint planning system also uses `sprint-status.yaml`. This story only writes to sprint-state.json per the epic definition. The generated stories won't appear in sprint-status.yaml unless manually added or a separate sync is run.\n\n**Observations:**\n- The existing `createFixStory()` in `validation-runner.ts` is a clean reference pattern. The audit fix generator is essentially the same concept applied to audit gaps instead of validation AC failures.\n- All 10 ACs are genuinely CLI-verifiable -- no workflow or external system dependencies. The audit module, file system operations, and sprint state can all be tested via unit tests and CLI invocations."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a7aea08ee42054500 (use SendMessage with to: 'a7aea08ee42054500' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 63894\ntool_uses: 35\nduration_ms: 192961</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0deb1693-f450-4ee3-ba9f-130c7ba0aec5","uuid":"204ac32e-8d67-40cd-925d-c9f39af00e0a","timestamp":"2026-03-20T09:14:55.274Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /create-story for story 3-2-audit-fix-story-generation. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` or `<!-- verification: integration-required -->` based on whether the AC can be verified by running CLI commands in a subprocess. ACs referencing workflows, sprint planning, user sessions, or external system interactions should be tagged as integration-required. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Problems encountered (errors, ambiguities in epic definition, missing context)\n- Workarounds applied (anything you did that felt hacky or suboptimal)\n- Risks identified (ACs that seem untestable, unclear requirements, missing dependencies)\n- Observations (anything surprising or noteworthy about this story)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`","agentId":"a7aea08ee42054500","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/3-2-audit-fix-story-generation.md`.\n\n**Summary:** Created story 3-2-audit-fix-story-generation with 10 acceptance criteria, 7 task groups, and detailed dev notes. All ACs tagged `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` -- every criterion can be verified by running CLI commands (build, test, run `codeharness audit --fix`, inspect output/files/state).\n\nThe story covers:\n- Fix story generation from audit gaps (FR15)\n- Sprint state integration via atomic writes\n- BMAD format compliance (NFR6)\n- Idempotency (skip existing stories)\n- JSON output support\n- Edge cases (0 gaps, missing state file, uninitialized harness)\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:**\n- None.\n\n**Workarounds applied:**\n- The epic definition (Story 3.2) has only 3 ACs. I expanded to 10 to cover edge cases, JSON output, idempotency, atomic writes, and precondition checks that are clearly needed based on existing codebase patterns. The original 3 ACs were too sparse for implementation.\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- **Story key collision:** The `audit-fix-{dimension}-{index}` key scheme uses a sequential index. If gaps change between runs (new gaps appear, old ones resolve), the same index could map to different gaps. A content-based hash would be more robust but harder to read. The dev should decide during implementation.\n- **Sprint-state.json vs sprint-status.yaml divergence:** The epic says \"added to sprint-state.json as backlog stories\" (AC #2), but the sprint planning system also uses `sprint-status.yaml`. This story only writes to sprint-state.json per the epic definition. The generated stories won't appear in sprint-status.yaml unless manually added or a separate sync is run.\n\n**Observations:**\n- The existing `createFixStory()` in `validation-runner.ts` is a clean reference pattern. The audit fix generator is essentially the same concept applied to audit gaps instead of validation AC failures.\n- All 10 ACs are genuinely CLI-verifiable -- no workflow or external system dependencies. The audit module, file system operations, and sprint state can all be tested via unit tests and CLI invocations."}],"totalDurationMs":192961,"totalTokens":63894,"totalToolUseCount":35,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4634,"cache_read_input_tokens":58702,"output_tokens":557,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4634},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
